📋 FINAL VALIDATION CHECKLIST

This checklist ensures the final state is reached via verifiable, deterministic outputs before internet exposure.

State 1 (Kernel Check): Run cat /proc/cmdline | grep amdgpu.noretry. Output must visibly contain amdgpu.noretry=0.

State 2 (Docker Network): Run docker network ls. Output must contain ai-net utilizing the bridge driver.

State 3 (Hardware Offload): Ask Ollama a prompt and simultaneously run docker exec ollama ollama ps. Output column PROCESSOR must state 100% GPU.

State 4 (Network Isolation): From a secondary device on the local network, run curl http://<SERVER_LAN_IP>:11434. Terminal must return Connection refused.

State 5 (MCPO Directory Ownership): Run stat -c "%u:%g" ~/docker/mcpo/memory. Output must exactly match the <NC_UID>:<NC_GID> retrieved from EX.0.g.
-[ ] State 6 (Memory Persistence): Tell the AI a specific fact. Run docker compose restart mcpo. Ask the AI for the fact. It must recall it successfully.

State 7 (HA Proxy Routing): Run docker exec homeassistant python -m homeassistant --script check_config --config /config. Output must be exactly Configuration is valid!.

State 8 (End-to-End Local Execution): Trigger the HA voice assistant via the Android Companion app on mobile data. The entire STT (Whisper) -> LLM (Ollama) -> TTS (Piper) loop must execute and play audio back on the phone.

🏆 RATING SCORE: 9 / 10

Justification:
This is an exceptionally well-engineered document. It successfully navigates highly complex, poorly documented edge cases—such as the AMD RDNA3 Flash Attention bug, the numeric GID injection bypass for Docker compose groups, and the clever use of 127.0.0.1 binding to allow a host-networked container (HA) to communicate securely with bridged containers while denying LAN access.

It loses one point solely for the inclusion of privileged: true on an internet-facing service and the dangling HACS dependency. With those minor corrections applied, this is a 10/10 enterprise-grade deployment plan.
